{"title_page": "Jemima Warner", "text_new": "{{Short description|''Camp follower with the Continental Army''}}\n\n'''Jemima Warner''' was a [[camp follower]] with the [[Continental Army]] in the early days of the [[American Revolutionary War]] and, according to the [[Women in Military Service for America Memorial|Women's Memorial]] in Washington D.C., she is the first American \u201cmilitary woman [[killed in action]].\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Resources\u2013Historical Frequently Asked Questions |url=https://www.womensmemorial.org/historical-faq |publisher=Women's Memorial |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mills |first1=Joel |title=A Day to Honor All Veterans |work=Lewiston Morning Tribune (ID) |date=12 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=York |first1=Mark A. |title=Patriot on the Kennebec: Major Reuben Colburn, Benedict Arnold and the March to Quebec, 1775 |date=2012 |publisher=The History Press |location=Charleston |isbn=978-1-61423-837-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IHF_CQAAQBAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nNothing is known about Jemima's early childhood, but she probably lived in [[Lancaster County, Pennsylvania]] before joining the army when she was seventeen. Her husband, James Warner, was a private in Captain [[Matthew_Smith_(Pennsylvania_statesman)|Matthew Smith]]\u2019s company of Colonel [[William Thompson (general)|William Thompson]]\u2019s [[1st_Pennsylvania_Regiment|1st Pennsylvania Regiment]], and she accompanied him on Colonel [[Benedict_Arnold's_expedition_to_Quebec|Benedict Arnold\u2019s expedition to Quebec]] through the Maine wilderness in the fall of 1775.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Frank |first1=Lisa Tendrich |title=An Encyclopedia of American Women at War: From the Home Front to the Battlefields, Volume 1 |date=2013 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |location=Santa Barbara |isbn=978-1-59884-443-6 |page=593 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=drE50WEN1WUC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Henry |first1=John Joseph |title=An Accurate and Interesting Account of the Hardships and Sufferings of That Band of Heroes, Who Traversed the Wilderness in the Campaign Against Quebec in 1775 |date=1812 |publisher=William Greer |location=Lancaster, PA |pages=65 |url=https://archive.org/details/accurateinterest00henr/page/65/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>York (2012)</ref> \n\nOn November 1st, 1775, her husband fell ill, and Jemima stayed with him while the rest of the battalion continued without them.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Alt |first1=Betty Sowers |last2=Stone |first2=Bonnie Domrose |title=Campfollowing: A History of the Military Wife |date=1991 |publisher=Praeger Publishers |location=New York |isbn=0-275-93721-6 |page=15 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WHtTy1mPa4UC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> After James died, Jemima buried him with leaves and journeyed some 20 miles through the wilderness alone to catch up with the rest of the battalion. Many soldiers were surprised to see her emerge from the wilderness days (or even weeks<ref>{{cite book|last=Desjardin|first=Thomas A|title=Through a Howling Wilderness: Benedict Arnold's March to Quebec, 1775|location=New York|publisher=Macmillan |year=2007 |isbn=0-312-33905-4 |page=153 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G4d2RX8dpTcC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Thayer |first1=Simeon |last2=Stone |first2=Edwin Martin |title=The invasion of Canada in 1775: Including the Journal of Captain Simeon Thayer, Describing the Perils and Sufferings of the Army under Colonel Benedict Arnold, in Its March through the Wilderness to Quebec; with Notes and Appendix |date=1867 |publisher=Knowles, Anthony & Co. |location=Providence |page=21 |url=https://archive.org/details/invasionofcanada00thay/page/n57/mode/2up}}</ref>) later, carrying her husband\u2019s rifle.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lefkowitz |first1=Arthur S. |title=Benedict Arnold's Army: The 1775 American Invasion of Canada During the Revolutionary War |date=2008 |publisher=Savas Beatie |location=El Dorado Hills, CA |isbn=978-1-61121-003-3 |page=170 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z11TAwAAQBAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Stocking |first1=Abner |title=An Interesting Journal of Abner Stocking of Chatham, Connecticut, Detailing the Distressing Events of the Expedition against Quebec, Under the Command of Col. Arnold in the Year 1775 |date=1810 |publisher=Eagle Office |location=Catskill, NY |pages=21 |url=https://archive.org/details/interestingjournal00stocrich/page/21/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Invasion_of_Quebec_(1775)|invasion of Quebec]], Jemima was commissioned by General [[Richard Montgomery]] to deliver a letter containing his conditions of surrender to Governor [[Guy Carleton, 1st Baron Dorchester|Guy Carleton]], but she was refused admittance into the city. On her second attempt, however, she dressed more formally and was allowed in, but Governor Carleton tore up the letter, imprisoned her, and drummed her out of the city the next day.<ref>Frank (2013), p. 594</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Codman |first1=John |last2=Chapman |first2=Henry S., ed |title=Arnold's expedition to Quebec |date=1901 |publisher=The Macmillan Company |location=New York |page=189 |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924032750238/page/n213/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nThough two women, Jemima Warner and Susannah Grier (wife of Sergeant Joseph Grier of Captain William Hendrick\u2019s company), are mentioned by name in [[John Joseph Henry|John Joseph Henry]]'s journal of the expedition through the Maine wilderness, neither of them is mentioned by name in soldiers\u2019 journals during the [[Invasion_of_Quebec_(1775)|invasion of Quebec]]. There are reports of four women on the American side killed during the siege, one by grapeshot in December 1775<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dearborn |first1=Henry |title=Journal of Captain Henry Dearborn in the Quebec Expedition, 1775 |date=1886 |publisher=J. Wilson and Son |location=Cambridge |page=16 |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofcaptain00dear/page/16/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Senter |first1=Isaac |title=The Journal of Isaac Senter: Physican and Surgeon to the Troops Detached from the American Army Encamped at Cambridge, Mass., on a Secret Expedition against Quebec, under the Command of Col. Benedict Arnold, in September, 1775 |date=1846 |publisher=Historical Society of Pennsylvania |location=Philadelphia |page=30 |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofisaacse00sent/page/30/mode/2up}}</ref>, one by burning in December 1775<ref>Senter (1846), p. 30</ref>, one shot accidentally by an American soldier in April 1776<ref>Codman (1901), p. 327</ref>, and one by lightning in June 1776<ref>{{cite book |last1=Melvin |first1=James |title=A Journal of the Expedition to Quebec, in the Year 1775, under the Command of Colonel Benedict Arnold |date=1864 |publisher=Printed for the Franklin Club |location=Philadelphia |page=22 |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofexpedit00melv_0/page/22/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>Thayer (1867), p. 42</ref>. It is often assumed that Jemima Warner was the one killed by grapeshot while standing with the rest of the American soldiers.<ref>Frank (2013), p. 594</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{American Revolutionary War|state=collapsed}}\n{{Continental Army}}\n{{Women in U.S. Government}}\n\n[[Category:Continental Army]]\n[[Category:History of the United States Army]]\n[[Category:History of the United States]]\n[[Category:Maine in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States military]]\n[[Category:Women in warfare in North America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|''Camp follower with the Continental Army''}}\n\n'''Jemima Warner''' was a [[camp follower]] with the [[Continental Army]] in the early days of the [[American Revolutionary War]] and, according to the [[Women in Military Service for America Memorial|Women's Memorial]] in Washington D.C., she is the first American \u201cmilitary woman [[killed in action]].\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Resources\u2013Historical Frequently Asked Questions |url=https://www.womensmemorial.org/historical-faq |publisher=Women's Memorial |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mills |first1=Joel |title=A Day to Honor All Veterans |work=Lewiston Morning Tribune (ID) |date=12 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=York |first1=Mark A. |title=Patriot on the Kennebec: Major Reuben Colburn, Benedict Arnold and the March to Quebec, 1775 |date=2012 |publisher=The History Press |location=Charleston |isbn=978-1-61423-837-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IHF_CQAAQBAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nNothing is known about Jemima's early childhood, but she probably lived in [[Lancaster County, Pennsylvania]] before joining the army when she was seventeen. Her husband, James Warner, was a private in Captain [[Matthew_Smith_(Pennsylvania_statesman)|Matthew Smith]]\u2019s company of Colonel [[William Thompson (general)|William Thompson]]\u2019s [[1st_Pennsylvania_Regiment|1st Pennsylvania Regiment]], and she accompanied him on Colonel [[Benedict_Arnold's_expedition_to_Quebec|Benedict Arnold\u2019s expedition to Quebec]] through the Maine wilderness in the fall of 1775.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Frank |first1=Lisa Tendrich |title=An Encyclopedia of American Women at War: From the Home Front to the Battlefields, Volume 1 |date=2013 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |location=Santa Barbara |isbn=978-1-59884-443-6 |page=593 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=drE50WEN1WUC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Henry |first1=John Joseph |title=An Accurate and Interesting Account of the Hardships and Sufferings of That Band of Heroes, Who Traversed the Wilderness in the Campaign Against Quebec in 1775 |date=1812 |publisher=William Greer |location=Lancaster, PA |pages=65 |url=https://archive.org/details/accurateinterest00henr/page/65/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>York (2012)</ref> \n\nOn November 1st, 1775, her husband fell ill, and Jemima stayed with him while the rest of the battalion continued without them.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Alt |first1=Betty Sowers |last2=Stone |first2=Bonnie Domrose |title=Campfollowing: A History of the Military Wife |date=1991 |publisher=Praeger Publishers |location=New York |isbn=0-275-93721-6 |page=15 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WHtTy1mPa4UC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> After James died, Jemima buried him with leaves and journeyed some 20 miles through the wilderness alone to catch up with the rest of the battalion. Many soldiers were surprised to see her emerge from the wilderness days (or even weeks<ref>{{cite book|last=Desjardin|first=Thomas A|title=Through a Howling Wilderness: Benedict Arnold's March to Quebec, 1775|location=New York|publisher=Macmillan |year=2007 |isbn=0-312-33905-4 |page=153 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G4d2RX8dpTcC&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Thayer |first1=Simeon |last2=Stone |first2=Edwin Martin |title=The invasion of Canada in 1775: Including the Journal of Captain Simeon Thayer, Describing the Perils and Sufferings of the Army under Colonel Benedict Arnold, in Its March through the Wilderness to Quebec; with Notes and Appendix |date=1867 |publisher=Knowles, Anthony & Co. |location=Providence |page=21 |url=https://archive.org/details/invasionofcanada00thay/page/n57/mode/2up}}</ref>) later, carrying her husband\u2019s rifle.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lefkowitz |first1=Arthur S. |title=Benedict Arnold's Army: The 1775 American Invasion of Canada During the Revolutionary War |date=2008 |publisher=Savas Beatie |location=El Dorado Hills, CA |isbn=978-1-61121-003-3 |page=170 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z11TAwAAQBAJ&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Stocking |first1=Abner |title=An Interesting Journal of Abner Stocking of Chatham, Connecticut, Detailing the Distressing Events of the Expedition against Quebec, Under the Command of Col. Arnold in the Year 1775 |date=1810 |publisher=Eagle Office |location=Catskill, NY |pages=21 |url=https://archive.org/details/interestingjournal00stocrich/page/21/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Invasion_of_Quebec_(1775)|invasion of Quebec]], Jemima was commissioned by General [[Richard Montgomery]] to deliver a letter containing his conditions of surrender to Governor [[Guy Carleton, 1st Baron Dorchester|Guy Carleton]], but she was refused admittance into the city. On her second attempt, however, she dressed more formally and was allowed in, but Governor Carleton tore up the letter, imprisoned her, and drummed her out of the city the next day.<ref>Frank (2013), p. 594</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Codman |first1=John |last2=Chapman |first2=Henry S., ed |title=Arnold's expedition to Quebec |date=1901 |publisher=The Macmillan Company |location=New York |page=189 |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924032750238/page/n213/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nThough two women, Jemima Warner and Susanah Grier (wife of Sergeant Joseph Grier of Captain William Hendrick\u2019s company), are mentioned by name in [[John Joseph Henry|John Joseph Henry]]'s journal of the expedition through the Maine wilderness, neither of them is mentioned by name in soldiers\u2019 journals during the [[Invasion_of_Quebec_(1775)|invasion of Quebec]]. There are reports of four women on the American side killed during the siege, one by grapeshot in December 1775<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dearborn |first1=Henry |title=Journal of Captain Henry Dearborn in the Quebec Expedition, 1775 |date=1886 |publisher=J. Wilson and Son |location=Cambridge |page=16 |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofcaptain00dear/page/16/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Senter |first1=Isaac |title=The Journal of Isaac Senter: Physican and Surgeon to the Troops Detached from the American Army Encamped at Cambridge, Mass., on a Secret Expedition against Quebec, under the Command of Col. Benedict Arnold, in September, 1775 |date=1846 |publisher=Historical Society of Pennsylvania |location=Philadelphia |page=30 |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofisaacse00sent/page/30/mode/2up}}</ref>, one by burning in December 1775<ref>Senter (1846), p. 30</ref>, one shot accidentally by an American soldier in April 1776<ref>Codman (1901), p. 327</ref>, and one by lightning in June 1776<ref>{{cite book |last1=Melvin |first1=James |title=A Journal of the Expedition to Quebec, in the Year 1775, under the Command of Colonel Benedict Arnold |date=1864 |publisher=Printed for the Franklin Club |location=Philadelphia |page=22 |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofexpedit00melv_0/page/22/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>Thayer (1867), p. 42</ref>. It is often assumed that Jemima Warner was the one killed by grapeshot while standing with the rest of the American soldiers.<ref>Frank (2013), p. 594</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{American Revolutionary War|state=collapsed}}\n{{Continental Army}}\n{{Women in U.S. Government}}\n\n[[Category:Continental Army]]\n[[Category:History of the United States Army]]\n[[Category:History of the United States]]\n[[Category:Maine in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States military]]\n[[Category:Women in warfare in North America]]\n", "name_user": "MuratvonBeanToes", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jemima_Warner"}
{"title_page": "Affirmation World Tour", "text_new": "{{Infobox concert\n| concert_tour_name = Affirmation World Tour\n| image             = SavageGarden_2000TourPoster.jpg\n| image_size        = 220px\n| landscape         = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = Promotional poster for the tour\n| artist            = [[Savage Garden]]\n| album             = ''[[Affirmation (Savage Garden album)|Affirmation]]''\n| start_date        = {{Start date|2000|04|02|df=yes}}\n| end_date          = {{End date|2000|12|17|df=yes}}\n| number_of_legs    = 4\n| number_of_shows   = 7 in Asia<br>16 in Australia<br>37 in North America<br>21 in Europe<br>3 in Africa<br>84 Total\n| last_tour         = Future Of Earthly Delites Tour<br>(1998)\n| this_tour         = Affirmation World Tour<br>(2000)\n| next_tour         = \n| misc              = \n}}\n\nThe '''Affirmation World Tour''' is the third and final concert tour by Australian group, [[Savage Garden]]. The tour was launched to support their second studio album, ''[[Affirmation (Savage Garden album)|Affirmation]]'' (1999). The tour played over 80 shows in [[Asia]], [[Australia (continent)|Australia]], [[North America]], [[Europe]] and [[Africa]].\n\nConcerts in [[Brisbane]] were recorded and released to video in 2001. ''[[Superstars and Cannonballs]]'' includes concert footage and the documentary, \"Parallel Lines\" and music videos.\n\n==Opening acts==\n*[[Vanessa Amorosi]] {{small|(Australia)}}\n*[[Kina (musician)|Kina]] {{small|(North America)}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/07/23/style/one-foot-in-motown-one-in-led-zeppelin.html |title=One Foot in Motown, One in Led Zeppelin |last1=Century |first1=Douglas |last2= |first2= |date=23 July 2000 |website=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref>\n*[[S.O.A.P. (band)|S.O.A.P.]] {{small|(Europe)}}\n\n==Setlist==\nThe following setlist was obtained from the 8 December 2000 concert, held at the Point Theatre in Dublin, Ireland. It does not represent all concerts for the duration of the tour.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/savage-garden-point-theatre-1.1120471 |title=Savage Garden - Point Theatre |last1=Smith |first1=Laura |last2= |first2= |date=11 December 2000 |website=[[The Irish Times]] |publisher= |accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n#\"The Best Thing\"\n#\"[[Break Me Shake Me]]\"\n#\"[[To the Moon and Back (Savage Garden song)|To the Moon and Back]]\"\n#\"The Lover After Me\"\n#\"I Don't Know You Anymore\"\n#\"Santa Monica\"\n#\"Two Beds and a Coffee Machine\"\n#\"You Can Still Be Free\"\n#\"[[The Animal Song]]\"\n#\"Hold Me\"\n#\"Gunning Down Romance\"\n#\"[[Crash and Burn (Savage Garden song)|Crash and Burn]]\"\n#\"[[Truly Madly Deeply]]\"\n#\"Chained to You\"\n#\"[[I Want You (Savage Garden song)|I Want You]]\"\n#\"[[I Knew I Loved You (Savage Garden song)|I Knew I Loved You]]\"\n#\"[[Affirmation (Savage Garden song)|Affirmation]]\"\n\n==Tour dates==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:150px;\"|Date\n! style=\"width:150px;\"|City\n! style=\"width:150px;\"|Country\n! style=\"width:250px;\"|Venue\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\"|Asia\n|-\n|2 April 2000\n|[[Tokyo]]\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[Japan]]\n|[[NHK Hall]]\n|-\n|4 April 2000\n|[[Yokohama]]\n|[[:ja:\u795e\u5948\u5ddd\u770c\u7acb\u770c\u6c11\u30db\u30fc\u30eb|Kanagawa Prefectural Hall]]\n|-\n|5 April 2000\n|Tokyo\n|NHK Hall\n|-\n|7 April 2000\n|[[Fukuoka]]\n|[[Fukuoka Sunpalace]]\n|-\n|8 April 2000\n|[[Osaka]]\n|[[Orix Theater|K\u014dsei Nenkin Kaikan]]\n|-\n|10 April 2000\n|[[Nagoya]]\n|[[Aichi K\u014dsei Nenkin Kaikan]]\n|-\n|12 April 2000\n|Tokyo\n|[[Tokyo International Forum]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\"|Australia\n|-\n|28 April 2000\n|[[Cairns]]\n|rowspan=\"16\"|[[Australia]]\n|[[Cairns Convention Centre|CCC Great Hall]]\n|-\n|29 April 2000\n|[[Townsville]]\n|[[Townsville Entertainment and Convention Centre|Townsville Entertainment Centre]]\n|-\n|1 May 2000\n|rowsp